Hey guys, love this conversation - happy to chime in. A few things are going on here, maybe I can shed some light. Omega can be large with high positive returns or with low losses. If you have no losses or fractional loss, your omega score will be quite large. We recently updated the fees structure to account for the amount of leverage used, so a transaction that takes place within one minute is almost guaranteed to result in a loss as the market isn't likely to make such large moves in a short period of time. We let the miners who were trading in the feeless system keep their scores, as they were the rules when we first kept the system - it will take a bit of time until historical decay augments them back to a return of 1 given that they had such large transactions. The sharpe ratio is meant to also encourage a more standard style of behavior, open to hearing your ideas for different combinations of metrics, but the omega was originally selected over the sharpe ratio as it seems to have some statistical benefits around discrepancies in investor psychology in losses vs gains (sharpe ratio sees big losses and big gains statistically the same, but there is a strong preference for a portfolio which only takes risk on the upside) as well as the lack of normality assumption with returns distributions: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Post-modern_portfolio_theory

The other thing is that the data you're pulling actually includes the scores from grace period miners, who don't need to have 10 transactions. Having less than 10 transactions increases the probability that there is no loss, which would make their omega astronomically high. These miners are not getting evaluated with the weights system, just getting enough incentive so that they don't get deregistered until they reach 10 closed positions 🙂 .

On the note of 10 minimum closed positions, happy to dive into the math a bit and tell you my logic, might have to send another message as discord is unhappy with my novel

The 10 minimum transactions is really meant to filter out random traders. If you assume that you have a collection of real traders with a sound strategy and the rest are randomly trading, there is a nonzero chance that random traders will get lucky on every trade and dominate the scoreboard. With the omega ratio, this can be simplified to the number of losses they're likely to take (think flipping a coin). If you have a room full of 200 @kabar miners all flipping coins (sorry kabar, I know you probably have a real strategy), we would like for the probability that any one of them has all heads to be incredibly low, sufficient enough that a random miner is statistically unlikely to ever be on top of the leaderboard at any given moment.

This also gives us greater statistical confidence in the output of the miners' risk adjusted metrics, which are used by the validators in selling their predictions via the request network. The greater confidence we can inspire in people who will buy the predictions, the more validators will set weights with our subnet, the more emissions we can provide to the miners 🤝

That being said, all of these things are open to suggestion 🙂 - would love to hear your ideas on how we should be managing the incentive structure, minimum positions, etc, and will be sharing updates with each change as well as the thought process.
